Different Modes of Transportation in the United States: Report

Lily Claire Gibson-Grossmann

2024-10-21

1 Introduction

1.1 Topic of Interest

This dataset provides a breakdown of commuters to work in the United States, highlighting five primary modes of transportation to work: Car/Truck/Van (Drove Alone), Car/Truck/Van (Carpooled), Walking, Taxicab/Motorcycle/Bicycle/Other, and Working From Home. I am interested in examining the trends in commuting methods over time, specifically looking at the rise of remote work and the trends of different modes of transportation in the United States.

The COVID-19 pandemic made a shift to working from home; I am curious to explore how this trend developed both before and after the pandemic. In addition, I am curious how different modes of transportation for commuting to work has changed over the years. Non-private transportation in the U.S. has limited availability, as the US primarily uses private transportation (individual cars). However, there are many benefits to using other modes of transit and I am curious if the US is diversifying our modes of transit in regard to commutes to work.

By examining these trends and correlations, we will gain insights into how commuting has evolved in the U.S. in the context of working from home and different modes of transportation.

1.2 Key Questions

In the U.S., how did the work-from-home (WFH) trend develop before COVID-19, and how has it evolved post-pandemic?

What was the trend of different modes of transportation in general leading up to the pandemic, and how has it shifted since the pandemic in the U.S.?

How have subcategories of different modes of transportation, such as carpooling or walking, changed over time in the U.S.?

1.3 Data Description

The data in this table is sourced from the U.S. Census Bureau through the American Community Survey (ACS). The data is collected from the ACS one-year estimates, which are collected annually throughout each year. By using one-year estimates instead of the alternative five-year estimates from the ACS, we get a better understanding of the current population. The sample data from each year is representative of the U.S. population, more specifically are applicable to geographies with a population of 65,000 people or more. This data might not be as representative of geographies with less than 65,000 people, and these samples are used for general U.S. population estimations.

The ASC data is collected continuously throughout the year using multiple ways. Some of these methods are sending out surveys via mail, conducting phone interviews, and using in-person visits to gather information (data) from a sample of households. The U.S. Census Bureau did not release the 2020 ACS 1-year estimates for this table due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The data was too low of quality to be considered, so instead the Census Bureau released experimental estimates in 2020 for a limited number of tables, which was not included in this table I chose. Therefore, we do not have data for the year 2020 in our dataset.

The dataset consists of 37 columns, giving a breakdown of commuters by their mode of transportation, which is the primary focus of this analysis. The data further subdivides each transportation mode based on the number of cars available to the commuter (e.g., no car, one car, etc.). We will not be considering these variables of the dataset given the questions we are exploring, but these additional variables could offer context for understanding the transportation choices of different commuter groups in future analysis.

Sources

  • Source: US Census Bureau
  • Source: U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics

To ensure our data can be integrated, I will standardize the column names, ensuring they are consistent across all years.

Given that the original column names are lengthy and not intuitively clear, I will create a key to represent each column as follows. This key focuses on the variables of our interest.

2.7 Change Column Type

We need to ensure our data is stored as integers. Currently, the data is stored as characters and has non-numerical characters, such as commas, within the strings. We can see this by using the ‘class’ R function for any one of our columns; the class that is returned is ‘character’ (not an integer).

class(data$Total)
## [1] "character"
class(data$`WFH T`)
## [1] "character"

The ‘as.integer’ R function will convert the figures from strings to integers. There will be an error, however, due to the presence of commas in the string. To overcome this error, the gsub R function will delete any comma in the string by replacing the comma with an empty value (““). This step is necessary for analysis.

data$Total <- as.integer(gsub(",", "", data$Total))
data$`CTV DA T` <- as.integer(gsub(",", "", data$`CTV DA T`))
data$`CTV C T` <- as.integer(gsub(",", "", data$`CTV C T`))
data$`W T` <- as.integer(gsub(",","", data$`W T`))
data$`TMBO T` <- as.integer(gsub(",", "", data$`TMBO T`))
data$`WFH T` <- as.integer(gsub(",", "", data$`WFH T`))
data$Year <- as.integer(data$Year)
view(data)

3 Analysis

3.1 Total Commute to Work Distribution Over Time

This graph shows the total number of commuters (e.g. the total sample) in the U.S. over time (2010 to 2023). The sample size for the number of commuters has grown over time, which is representative of the population growth in the urban cities (population of 65k people or more) in the U.S.. As urban cities have grown in the U.S., sample size is increased to more accurately represent the population.

From the graph, we can see that the total number of commuters in the U.S. in 2021 is noticeably lower or an outlier compared to previous years; when we subset the data, this remains true for the year 2021. This trend can be attributed to the widespread and ongoing effects of the COVID-19 pandemic during that period. The pandemic created challenges for the American Community Survey (ACS) in collecting data, thus had less samples in comparison to other years.

Source: US Census Bureau

3.2 Linear Model: Total Commute to Work Distribution Over Time

A linear regression line has been added using geom_smooth(method = “lm”) to illustrate the general trend in population changes over time. The shaded area around the line represents the 95% confidence interval, reflecting the uncertainty of the trend’s fit. From this linear model, we can again see that overall, there is a positive relationship between the total sample size and time. This shows that over time, the samples being drawn by the ACS is growing to more accurately reflect the U.S. population.

Source: US Census Bureau

3.3 Car/Truck/Van (Drove Alone) Commute to Work Distribution

For the subset of commuters who used a car, truck, or van (driving alone) to commute to work, the number of commuters grew at a relatively steady rate over time. However, in 2021, there was a sharp decline due to the COVID-19 pandemic, as previously mentioned. The number of commuters doesn’t reach the peak it was at prior to the pandemic, indicating that after the pandemic less people are driving alone. This is likely due to work from home along with other different modes of transit growing during and after the pandemic, which will be seen in later analysis.

Correlation will help us understand the magnitude of the growth for the mode of transportation for the commute in relation to time (years). The closer to 1 (or -1), the stronger the relationship, indicating that mode of transport was heavily increasing (or decreasing) year by year. Inversely, the closer to 0 the correlation is indicates the weaker the relationship.

The overall correlation between these commuters and time (years) is relatively weak, with a correlation coefficient of 0.3752, indicating a small relationship between time and the growth of commuters. This weaker correlation is likely skewed by the significant drop in 2021.

cor(data$`CTV DA T`, data$Year)
## [1] 0.3752721

To better understand the trend, accounting for the previously stated drop in 2021, the data can be divided into pre- and post-COVID periods. Before the pandemic, the correlation between commuters and time was very strong, with a coefficient of 0.9965. After the pandemic, the correlation remained strong at 0.9682. This shows a robust relationship between time and the number of car/truck/van (drove alone) commuters. Overall, the number of car/truck/van (drove alone) commuters in the U.S. has increased over time.

pre_covid <- data %>% filter(data$Year < 2021)
post_covid <- data %>% filter(data$Year >= 2021)
cor(pre_covid$`CTV DA T`, pre_covid$Year)
## [1] 0.9965433
cor(post_covid$`CTV DA T`, post_covid$Year)
## [1] 0.9682169

3.4 Car/Truck/Van (Carpooled) Commute to Work Distribution

For the subset of commuters who used a car, truck, or van (carpooling) to commute to work, the number of commuters grew at a somewhat steady rate over time; we can see much more variability in the carpooled data versus the driving alone data. As previously mentioned, in 2021, there was a sharp decline due to the COVID-19 pandemic.

The overall correlation between these commuters and time (years) is weak, with a correlation coefficient of 0.2141. This indicates a small relationship between time and the growth of car/truck/van (carpooling) commuters over the whole time period (2010 - 2023).

cor(data$`CTV C T`, data$Year)
## [1] 0.2141343

As previously stated, we can break our data into pre-COVID and post-COVID datasets to better understand the correlations. Before the pandemic, the correlation between commuters and time was moderately strong, with a coefficient of 0.7748. After the pandemic, the correlation grew in strength, rising to 0.9718. This shows that before the COVID-19 pandemic, the number of car/truck/van (carpooling) commuters in the U.S. was growing, and after the pandemic this mode of transportation has started increasing more heavily.

cor(pre_covid$`CTV C T`, pre_covid$Year)
## [1] 0.7748086
cor(post_covid$`CTV C T`, post_covid$Year)
## [1] 0.9717854

3.5 Walked Commute to Work Distribution

For the subset of commuters who walked to commute to work, the number of commuters grew at a somewhat steady rate over time. We can see some variability overall, with this mode of transportation decreasing some starting around 2015. As previously mentioned, in 2021, there was a sharp decline due to the COVID-19 pandemic. After the pandemic, we can see an increase in the trend start again, potentially indicating that after the pandemic, walking to work has been an increasing mode of transportation.

The overall correlation between these commuters and time (years) is weak, with a correlation coefficient of -0.3548, indicating a weak relationship between time and the growth of commuters between 2010 to 2023 (excluding 2020). The negative coefficient, in general, shows that as one variable increases, the other variable decreases. The negative correlation does not indicate a more strong/weak correlation, but instead shows if the correlation is positively or negatively associated.

cor(data$`W T`, data$Year)
## [1] -0.3547618

Before the pandemic, the correlation between commuters and time was moderately strong, with a coefficient of 0.7159. After the pandemic, the correlation grew in strength, rising to 0.9385. This shows that before the COVID-19 pandemic, the number of walking commuters in the U.S. was growing, and after the pandemic this mode of transportation has started increasing more heavily.

cor(pre_covid$`W T`, pre_covid$Year)
## [1] 0.7159188
cor(post_covid$`W T`, post_covid$Year)
## [1] 0.9384823

For the subset of commuters who used a taxicab, motorcycle, bicycle, or other to commute to work, the number of commuters grew at a somewhat steady rate over time. We can see more variability to this trend over time, although we still do see a general increase in the graph. We see less of a sharp drop in this mode of transportation in 2021, although still a drop. This could be due to a number of factors, such as this subset of the population continuing to need their mode of transportation throughout the COVID-19 pandemic.

The overall correlation between these commuters and time (years) is very strong, with a correlation coefficient of 0.9598, indicating a very strong relationship between time and the growth of commuters throughout the time period. The previous graphs we have seen had a less strong correlation over the whole time period, but likely due to the more minor of a drop we see in this data for the year 2021, our overall data is less skewed hence more correlated.

## [1] 0.9598197

Before the pandemic, the correlation between commuters and time was also very strong, with a coefficient of 0.9543. After the pandemic, the correlation remained strong, with a coefficient of 0.9314. This shows that before and after the COVID-19 pandemic, the number of commuters who used a taxicab, motorcycle, bicycle, or other to commute to work in the U.S. has been growing and is strongly correlated with time.

3.7 Worked From Home Commute to Work Distribution

For the subset of commuters who work from home, the number of commuters grew at a somewhat steady rate over time before the pandemic, with a drop after the pandemic. We can see that WFH, although growing, was much smaller before versus after the pandemic. At the peak the COVID-19 pandemic, there was a sharp increase in people working from home. We are now in a period of companies slowly decreasing their WFH employees.

The overall correlation between these commuters and time (years) is moderately strong, with a correlation coefficient of 0.8262. This shows that overall, the number of people working from home in the U.S. has been growing.

cor(data$`WFH T`, data$Year)
## [1] 0.8262338

Before the pandemic, the correlation between commuters and time was very strong, with a coefficient of 0.9691. After the pandemic, the correlation became negative and still strong with a coefficient of -0.9894. This shows that before the COVID-19 pandemic, the number of people working from home in the U.S. was growing, and after the pandemic this mode of transportation has started decreasing heavily with the rise of companies stopping and slowing working from home culture.

cor(pre_covid$`WFH T`, pre_covid$Year)
## [1] 0.9690568
cor(post_covid$`WFH T`, post_covid$Year)
## [1] -0.9893943

From this graph, we can see each of the 5 different modes of transportation broken down by color. Here, we can see that the most frequent mode of transportation in the U.S. is using a car/van/truck (driving alone). Before the pandemic, using a car/van/truck (carpooling) would have been the second most common mode of transportation, but after the pandemic now working from home is the second most common mode of transportation, with carpooling moved to the third most common mode of transit. Before the pandemic WFH was the third most common mode of transit. Walking and taxicab/motorcycle/bicycle/other come in close for fourth and fifth, but overall walking is slightly more common than taxicab/motorcycle/bicycle/other is for a mode of transit to work. This trend has remained the same before and after the pandemic.

4 Conclusion

In conclusion, the U.S. relies more heavily on cars and individual modes of transportation (private transit) compared to many other developed nations, which can be seen in the data through the car/truck/van (driving alone) mode of transport being the most common both before and after the pandemic. There are many factors as to why the U.S. is more reliant on individual/private transportation than other nations; the expansion of urban cities, infrastructure designed around individual cars, limited public transportation, and the cultural usage of cars in the states are some examples.

However, there’s a shift in the U.S. towards different modes of transportation beyond private vehicles. For example, we firstly can see that after the pandemic, commuters who drive alone decreased significantly and hasn’t reached its peak levels prior to the pandemic. This shows that after the pandemic, less people are driving alone versus prior to the pandemic. We also see that carpooling saw significant growth before the pandemic, with a correlation coefficient with time (years) of 0.7748, rising to 0.9718 after the pandemic, showing that carpooling is gaining over time. Walking to work has also grown, with a pre-pandemic correlation coefficient of 0.7159, increasing to 0.9385 post-pandemic, indicating an upward trend. Those commuting using taxicab/motorcycle/bicycle/other has strong growth, with a correlation coefficient of 0.9544 pre-pandemic and 0.9314 post-pandemic, showing that this mode of transit continues to rise. Working from home, which had been gradually increasing before the pandemic (correlation coefficient of 0.9691), saw a dramatic increase between 2019 and 2021, jumping from roughly 8.8 million to roughly 27.3 million people due to the COVID-19 pandemic. However, as we move back to in-person work, there’s a significant decline in WFH, reflected by a post-pandemic correlation coefficient of -0.9894, indicating that WFH is rapidly decreasing over time.

While the U.S. still primarily relies on private, individual transportation, it’s clear that other forms of transit are becoming more popular over time, especially after the pandemic, with most categories of transit experiencing more growth (stronger correlation) in the post-pandemic era. Work from home is the exception, as now that we are in the post-pandemic era, work from home is declining as more people are moving back to in-person work.
